<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1762,2024]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41">
Female characterized by first to third pairs of dorsocentral setae (c 
<number box="[931,939,1779,1793]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
, d 
<number box="[969,977,1779,1793]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
and e 
<number box="[1047,1055,1779,1793]" pageId="8" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
) which are progressively longer towards rear, first pair about half as long as distances to bases of second pair; dorsal body setae generally long, setose and tapering but somewhat widened. Dorsal striations bear rounded lobes with basal spots. Aedeagus somewhat straight, narrowing distally to a relatively slender neck before ending in small angulations with anterior ventral angulation being acute and the distal dorsal one being very slightly curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
